<br>
I agree Dusty  I have come to believe that  a laminated plate composed of layers M2 tool and die steel (tungsten alloy) and a suitable ceramic is a possibility that should be investigated. The plate is going to erode no matter what its composition so the ticket might be to design it so that it does so in a controlled fashion.<br>
<br>
What I think would be ideal would be a slightly convex structure such as the one the original team proposed. With that geometry the plasma can wash over the plate and not leave a pool of hot plasma in the center to eat away at the plate. The only difference would be that the pusher plate now has two major components: <br>
1) The composite erosion shield<br>
2) The structural support plate <br>
<br>
<br>
 Quote: “ If the pusher plate was magnetised with superconducting coils, could this absorb the impulse of the plasma with reduced (or even zero) actual physical contact (it would probably generate fairly impressive EMP though!! )”<br>
<br>
I think that this concept has a great deal of merit although I don’t know how much electrical power would be necessary to generate a field strong enough to accomplish the task. Of course the beauty of  EPPP is that the pulse units can be designed so that they do not overload the system. I don’t think that  EMP is going to be a problem for an Orion that is a space only system. Also the equipment  onboard the ship could be shielded against the EMP.  <br>
<br>
I have never believed that a fast pulse rate of say 2 per second was even remotely possible simply because of the dud rate for nuclear devises. I read that you could expect a dud rate of about 1 percent. The rapid fire devise that the original designers envisioned required some very fine timing in the detonation of the bombs. I believe that they wanted  to time the detonations so that the blast actually provided a cushion for the plate as it neared battery. The problem was that the heavy plate might just pop off if a bomb failed to detonate. <br>
<br>
I also agree that Orion would work best with a slow pulse rate of say one every five seconds and then it could be equipped with the heavy return dampening that you mentioned.  Thanks for the response Dusty<br>
