    In your haste to insult Tim over his answers on pusher plates, you stubbed your own toe just a bit. The &quot;Orion&quot; book is not by Freeman Dyson, but his son George. You knew that of course (and I am sure that you have been told before that anonymous insults on bulletin boards achieve nothing).<br>
Perhaps it's been on this list before (I am new), but another superb book on the history of Orion is &quot;The Starship and the Canoe&quot; by Kenneth Brower. Published in 1983, it is a profile of Freeman, the gifted astrophysicist, and his counterculture son, George, who spent his time in the 70s and early 80s living in a treehouse and making delicate, wooden ocean-going canoes. Its theme was that for all his rebelliousness, George Dyson was very much like the father that he (then) rejected out of opposition to anything to do with nukes. This book of course lacks that technical detail in the book that George has now written on the project. Son George seems to have come full circle in his appraisal of his father's work for the Orion project. And on the topic of technical detail, Dyson reports that the original Orion team was quite convinced that ablation of the pusher plate is not a serious threat to the idea. Study of materials exposed to close nuclear blasts, and modeling on the crude computers of that day, indicated that the plate's surface, over a broad range of possible materials, would lose at most a few thousandths of an inch of thickness per blast, and that very thin coatings of oil (even greasy fingerprints) stopped all ablation. The plasma from the propellant lasts such a brief time that its high temperature did not have time to do much harm,it appears. At any rate, if the original designers of Orion, some of the most brilliant physicists and materials science experts of the last century, felt ablation is no biggie, I can't see why a list serve of random enthusiasts should spend a lot of time worrying about it. <br>
<br>
